File: The decline in sales is reportedly due to COVID-19 related trading restrictions imposed worldwide. JOHANNESBURG - Steinhoff International Holdings has reported a 6% decline in sales for the nine-months to the end of June. This is due to COVID-19 related trading restrictions imposed worldwide. READ: NPA still investigating Steinhoff scandal Steinhoff has been selling off assets and is battling for survival after uncovering a more than R100-billion hole in its accounts in 2017. This caused a share collapse and multiple lawsuits from former business partners and aggrieved shareholders. Locally the retailer Pepkor Africa division lost about R5.7-billion in sales to the national lockdown.